XIV. 1 The most natural measure of the value of any thing is the need for it, as Aristotle rightly shows: which is seen most clearly in the exchange of things amongst barbarians. Yet this is not the only measure. For the will of men, which is the master of things, desii-es many things more than are necessary. Pearls, says Pliny, derive their valae from luxury. And so Cicero of pictures: the measure of man's desires in these tliingys is the measure of valae. And, on the other hand, it comes to pass that the most necessary things are of small value for their abundance.
